However, performance tests (N=500,1000,1500) show runtimes ~4.7s, 17.2s, 42.5s respectively, indicating O(N^2) behavior that will time out on the problem's maximum constraints (sum N up to 2e5). The code is straightforward and documented with minimal comments and a useful docstring, but it is a brute-force O(N^2) solution (nested loops over couples) so it is not efficient or highly maintainable for large inputs. Overall the logic is correct for small inputs and edge cases, but it is not scalable under the stated constraints, hence the reduced correctness and simplicity/robustness scores.
